IV. Other parties, in going to war, allege justificatory causes, which, when brought to the standard os right reason, turn out unjust3 and then it appears, as Livy says, that what is aimed at is, not a trial of right, but of strength. Most kings, says Plutarch, use the two nameS, peace and war, only as coins, to procure, not what is just, but what is expedient. What are unjust causes, may be known in some measure from tho just causes which we have been explaining: the straight line is the index of what is oblique. But for the sake of perspicuity we shall make some general remarks.
